#Text=Diving in East Timor
#Text=Timor-Leste
#Text=has some of the best dive sites in the world due to its location , warm waters , minimal tourist trade and lack of commercial fishing or heavy industry .

#Text=Situated in the Coral Triangle , Timor is surrounded by deep water ( about 2,500 m between Liquiçá and Alor Island , Indonesia ) that gives home to an abundance of coral and fish life , including the annual migration of whales through the Ombai Strait and Wetar Strait according to a Marine Megafauna Survey in Timor Leste of June 2009 .
#Text=However , those same deep waters can cause strong currents at even the most protected sites so check the Tidal Predictions beforehand .
#Text=High tide and days of smaller variation are usually better .
#Text=Always have a good look at the water before entering .
#Text=While many of the dive sites can be reached by land , some of these entry points require a long walk over coral , a long surface swim or a boat .
#Text=Listed below are some of the popular dive sites in Timor-Leste , but there are plenty more if you are adventurous or have a boat to get to those hard to reach places .
#Text=Remember , always dive safely
#Text=and in accordance with current dive regulations and procedures .
#Text=Note security precautions topside , cultural sensitivities such as the sacred trees at K41 and private property issues .
#Text=Nun 's Tree
#Text=General .
#Text=( This information is unconfirmed and maybe out of date ) .
#Text=Location .
#Text=Coordinates : 8°37'1"S 125°10'48"E see Wikimapia Satellite Map .
#Text=Near Nun 's clinic .
#Text=Entry .
#Text=Profile .
#Text=Points of interest .
#Text=Large giant clam ( ~1 meter ) , black tipped reef sharks , turtles .
#Text=Topside .
#Text=Seal Rock Maubara
#Text=General .
#Text=This is a nice dive , easily found , but dangerous currents in all directions have been encountered , including a strong downward/northerly one .
#Text=Until more data is collected , this is considered an advanced adventure dive for experienced divers .
#Text=Safety marker buoys and gloves in particular are essential .
#Text=Tight buddy teams and conservative diving well within no-deco and minimum air limits are also recommended given the potential for sudden changes in the situation .
#Text=A stand-by boat would be optimal .
#Text=Have a good look at the water 's surface before entering .
#Text=Location .
#Text=Coordinates : 8°36'41"S 125°11'33"E see Wikimapia Satellite Map .
#Text=From Maubara Fort , drive 1.2 km west and look for the large seal shaped rock on the right .
#Text=Park on the road .
#Text=Entry .
#Text=Gear up at the car , negotiate a low wall , and go straight in on either side of the rock .
#Text=Although an easy entry initially , at low tide the coral is very close to the surface , so fin-up early or dive on high tide .
#Text=Profile .
#Text=The slope dips away slowly at first , then drops off quickly to 30 m or more .
#Text=Follow the shoreline and enjoy nice coral gardens with lots of " bombies " and creatures to see including bat fish , nudibranchs , flute fish , lobsters and others .
#Text=On the west side of Seal Rock there is plenty to see both at depth and in the shallows , but note safety issues above .
#Text=As of June 2012 the east side is yet to be explored .
#Text=Top Side .
#Text=There is plenty of parking beside the road , but no shade .
#Text=However , Maubara , its shade and amenities are close by .
#Text=Maubara Church aka Kindergarten
#Text=General .
#Text=Although getting mixed reviews , there is still plenty to see on this coral slope with some good gardens and lots of creatures to be seen .
#Text=In close proximity to Maubara ( see “ topside ” , below ) and with plenty of shady parking , this is a great place for a picnic , sun-baking , snorkelling and diving .
#Text=Location .
#Text=Coordinates : 8°36'36"S 125°12'7"E , see Wikimapia Satellite Map .
#Text=From Liquiçá , drive through Maubara past the fort , cross the small river , past the Church and an old , disused , chalet style building on the right .
#Text=Immediately after that building , turn right onto the track leading to the beach and large shady trees , about 150 m west of the Church .
#Text=Entry .
#Text=Easy entry straight out from the car parking area ( NNW ) , although better to walk west for 50 m before entering , over sand and small rocks .
#Text=Profile .
#Text=Enter , swim out 50 – 100 m then turn west along the lovely coral slope , sprinkled with sandy patches , plenty of bombies ( coral outcrops ) and an abundance of sea life .
#Text=Beware of currents on this semi-exposed site .
#Text=Average depth 15 m , max 28 m.
#Text=Points of interest .
#Text=Bat fish , lion fish , assorted nudibranchs , crabs , the occasional spotted ray or shark , and dolphins and whales ( November to January ) .
#Text=Topside .
#Text=At Maubara there are local products on sale at the road side stalls .
#Text=The historic Dutch fort is usually open for inspection and the restaurant within it serves a good meal or coffee quickly and at reasonable prices , under the shade of some magnificent trees .
#Text=Be prepared for local spectators and curious children whilst on the beach !
#Text=Maubara Fort
#Text=General .
#Text=This infrequently dived location has some good coral on a sloping , sandy bottom , although parts of it have been washed away .
#Text=Location .
#Text=Coordinates : 8°36'34"S 125°12'15"E , see Wikimapia Satellite Map .
#Text=Entry .
#Text=Entry in front of the fort , down the steep steps of the sea wall and out over the easy entry sandy bottom .
#Text=Profile .
#Text=The usual profile is to head straight out ( NW ) over the gradual sandy slope , then turn right and follow the slope roughly east/SE until ready to turn around .
#Text=Average depth 8 m , max 18 m.
#Text=Points of interest .
#Text=Large nudibranchs , some “ spanish dancing worms ” , some unusual soft corals , big shrimps , eels , clams and some larger fish .
#Text=Topside .
#Text=As per Maubara Church , however there is no shade close to the entry point .
#Text=Bubble Beach
#Text=General .
#Text=Although difficult to find underwater , this is worth the effort .
#Text=Like most dive sites around Timor-Leste , the currents can vary from calm to hazardous and visibility can vary from stunning to poor .
#Text=A fence effectively denies access to the beach , although a number of dives have been undertaken when the fence has collapsed or divers have walked from the road to the beach .
#Text=Location .
#Text=Coordinates : 8°34'30"S 125°22'7"E , see Wikimapia Satellite Map , about 30 km from Dili and about 4 km before Liquica .
#Text=After coming over a headland with a religious station on it , the dive site is in front of an old , walled Indonesian memorial .
#Text=Entry .
#Text=Nice sandy slope .
#Text=Profile .

#Text=Head straight out ( NNW ) from the old Indonesian memorial on a bearing of ( needs information)° for about ( needs information ) m to find the bombies and , possibly , the sharks at about 30 m depth .
#Text=Alternatively , head NW until the slope drops away to a maximum of about 18 m and turn due west .
#Text=The NE profile drops to about 27 m and is mostly sand .
#Text=Points of interest .
#Text=Large , picturesque bombies and soft corals on a sandy bottom at about 30 m ( straight out ) or 15 to 5 m ( half left ) .
#Text=In places , the sand is warm and bubbles leak from the sea bed ( needs information ) .
#Text=Sharks , barracuda , lobster , nudibranchs , garden eels , blue spotted rays , triggers , puffers , morays , lizards , squirrels , parrots , angels and butterfly fish .
#Text=Topside .
#Text=No shade close to the entry point – fence
